(* ### Problem
 Consider the dark square in an array of unit squares, part of which is shown. The first ring of squares around this center square contains 8 unit squares. The second ring contains 16 unit squares. If we continue this process, then what is the number of unit squares in the $100^{th}$ ring?

[asy]
fill((2,2)--(7,2)--(7,7)--(2,7)--cycle,gray(0.8));
fill((3,3)--(6,3)--(6,6)--(3,6)--cycle,gray(0.6));
fill((4,4)--(4,5)--(5,5)--(5,4)--cycle,black);
for (int i=0; i<10; ++i) {
draw((0,i)--(9,i));
draw((i,0)--(i,9));
}
[/asy] The final Answer is 800
 ### Proof
 The $n^{th}$ ring can be partitioned into four rectangles: two containing $2n+1$ unit squares and two containing $2n-1$ unit squares.
 So there are $$2(2n+1)+2(2n-1) = 8n$$ unit squares in the $n^{th}$ ring.
 Thus, the $100^{th}$ ring has $8 \cdot 100 = \boxed{800}$ unit squares.
 *)

theorem
fixes n :: nat
assumes h0 : "n = 100"
shows  "8 * n = 800"
 proof- 
  show ?thesis sledgehammer

